TI  - Causality-driven, interpretable surrogate modeling for DOAS preheating control
AU  - Mun, J. Y.
AU  - Jo, H. G.
AU  - Kim, J. H.
AU  - Park, C. S.
AU  - Urabe, E.
AU  - Mun, J. H.
AU  - Park, Y. S.
PY  - 2026
JO  - Energy and Buildings, Vol. 350, 116625.
DO  - 10.1016/j.enbuild.2025.116625
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378778825013556
AB  - Dedicated outdoor air systems (DOAS) that supply 100% outdoor air require reliable, model-based preheating control to prevent freezing and reduce energy consumption. This study introduces a causality-driven surrogate model, or a linear double machine learning simulator, for the preheating coil in a DOAS. A calibrated, high-fidelity physics-based simulator generated the training data. The resulting surrogate achieved predictive accuracy comparable to the full simulator while producing interpretable coefficients that describe the context-dependent causal impact of valve opening. This combination of predictive fidelity and causal interpretability enables efficient real-time optimization of preheating control.
