AB  - Scalability of data-driven dynamic models is a major challenge for practical model predictive control in buildings. This study develops a physics-informed, neural-network-implanted state-space (NNiSS) model to predict indoor, heat-pump return, and heat-pump supply air temperatures. The NNiSS model was compared with three conventional neural-network structures with different levels of dynamic interconnection. It consistently outperformed the alternatives when predicting beyond the trained inputs, showing that bidirectional propagation of physical relationships can improve model scalability for intelligent-building control.
